SourceString: "The Emperor's Missing Clothes" by Archibald Runt
Emperor Exutus awoke to a fine summers morning.
He stretched, yawned, then rose out of his bed and walked over to his window.
Outside he could see the beloved capital of the nation he ruled below.
He felt the warmth of the summer sun, and a gentle cool breeze.
In fact... He noticed the breeze felt quite a bit more fresh than it usually did...
That's when Emperor Exutus noticed that he was wearing no clothes!

He quickly ducked below his window so as to not accidentally
bless the eyes of any unsuspecting citizens below.
He remembered donning his imperial pyjamas the night before - where could they have gone?
Emperor Exutus crawled his way to his imperial wardrobe to look for something new to wear.
But everything was gone from there too!
He then checked the door to his bedroom and noticed it had been tampered with.
Someone had broken in! But who?!
Emperor Exutus stepped outside of his bedroom
only to find a servant turn the corner in the hallway and spot him.
The servant stopped in their tracks, stunned. The timing couldn't have been worse!
"Servant! Did you see anyone suspicious here?" said Emperor Exutus.

"Uhh... N-no me Emperor Lord" the servant replied, still visibly shocked
by his raw, bare-skinned, garmentless Emperor before him.
Emperor Exutus had to think fast.
"What do you think of my new robes?" asked the Emperor.
"Th-they're beautiful m-me Emperor Lord" the servant replied.
"That's right, they are. Now carry on."
The servant hurried past ensuring his gaze did not meet divine body of his Emperor.
Emperor Exutus thought for a moment.
He felt liberated in his new robes.
And it's not like anyone could question him. He is Emperor after all.
And thus, the Emperor ruled over his nation in the nude from that day forth.
The end.
The morale of the story: Lying solves everything, if you have enough power.
But also: Security is a serious matter.

And Emperor Exutus wouldn't have been if this situation if he had
gone with MEGA-LOCKS' brand new Bulwhark Mark III padlock.
